<highlight>
<T1>the germanwings jet crashed in a remote and difficult-to-reach area of the bleone valley in the french alps.</T1>

<T1.1>the crash site is located in a steep, mountainous region with no road access.</T1.1>
<T1.1.1>the aircraft crashed on the trois eveches mountain, a particularly steep spot.</T1.1.1>
<T1.1.2>captain benoit zeisser from the local gendarmerie confirmed the plane is lying in "difficult terrain."</T1.1.2>
<T1.1.3>emergency crews are being brought in by air using helicopters because roads cannot reach the site.</T1.1.3>

<T1.2>the valley is sparsely populated with tiny, often abandoned villages scattered along the gorge.</T1.2>
<T1.2.1>many villages that were bustling in the 19th century now lie abandoned or have only a handful of inhabitants.</T1.2.1>
<T1.2.2>one dead-end road, the d107, winds through the area but does not reach the crash site.</T1.2.2>

<T1.3>local residents witnessed or heard the crash.</T1.3>
<T1.3.1>sandrine boisse from the pra loup ski resort initially mistook the noise for an avalanche.</T1.3.1>
<T1.3.2>her husband was skiing nearby and saw a plane flying at low altitude.</T1.3.2>
<T1.3.3>skiers on the slopes may have witnessed the crash.</T1.3.3>

<T1.4>emergency response efforts are underway despite the difficult location.</T1.4>
<T1.4.1>french president francois hollande warned it would take hours for emergency services to reach the site.</T1.4.1>
<T1.4.2>helicopters and emergency vehicles are preparing to transport victims' remains.</T1.4.2>
<T1.4.3>a gymnasium at a local high school in seyne les alpes will be used as a temporary morgue.</T1.4.3>
<T1.4.4>french police urged locals and visitors to stay away and keep roads clear for emergency vehicles.</T1.4.4>
</highlight>